05008nam a22006855i 9780813541389DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20072007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135413897 a10.36019/97808135413892doi  a(DE-B1597)530193  a(OCoLC)1163878600  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGN484b.T734 2007 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a392.100aTranscultural Bodies :bFemale Genital Cutting in Global Context /cBettina K Shell-Duncan, Ylva K Hernlund. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface -- t1. Transcultural Positions: Negotiating Rights and Culture -- t2. Gender Crusades: The Female Circumcision Controversy in Cultural Perspective -- t3. A Refuge from Tradition and the Refuge of Tradition: On Anticircumcision Paradigms -- t4. Female Circumcision in Africa and Beyond: The Anthropology of a Difficult Issue -- t5. Persistence of Tradition or Reassessment of Cultural Practices in Exile? Discourses on Female Circumcision among and about Swedish Somalis -- t6. Managing Cultural Diversity in Australia: Legislating Female Circumcision, Legislating Communities -- t7. Representing Africa in the Kasinga Asylum Case -- t8. Seeking Asylum, Debating Values, and Setting Precedents in the 1990s: The Cases of Kassindja and Abankwah in the United States -- t9. Making Mandinga or Making Muslims? Debating Female Circumcision, Ethnicity, and Islam in Guinea-Bissau and Portugal -- t10. Infibulation and the Orgasm Puzzle: Sexual Experiences of Infibulated Eritrean Women in Rural Eritrea and Melbourne, Australia -- t11. Experiencing Sex in Exile: Can Genitals Change Their Gender? On Conceptions and Experiences Related to Female Genital Cutting (FGC) among Somalis in Norway -- t12. "Ain't I a Woman Too?": Challenging Myths of Sexual Dysfunction in Circumcised Women -- t13. The Failure of Pluralism? -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFemale "circumcision" or, more precisely, female genital cutting (FGC), remains an important cultural practice in many African countries, often serving as a coming-of-age ritual. It is also a practice that has generated international dispute and continues to be at the center of debates over women's rights, the limits of cultural pluralism, the balance of power between local cultures, international human rights, and feminist activism. In our increasingly globalized world, these practices have also begun immigrating to other nations, where transnational complexities vex debates about how to resolve the issue. Bringing together thirteen essays, Transcultural Bodies provides an ethnographically rich exploration of FGC among African diasporas in the United Kingdom, Europe, and Australia. Contributors analyze changes in ideologies of gender and sexuality in immigrant communities, the frequent marginalization of African women's voices in debates over FGC, and controversies over legislation restricting the practice in immigrant populations.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aFemale circumcision. 0aInfibulation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aHernlund, Ylva K, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShell-Duncan, Bettina K, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813541389.jpg  a978-3-11-06633